Moluccans are the Austronesian-speaking and Papuan-speaking ethnic groups inhabiting the Maluku Islands. The term "Moluccan" is an umbrella term that covers the various Austronesian and Papuan languages spoken on the islands. The largest group of Moluccans are the Tolo-speaking people.

The Maluku Islands are a group of volcanic islands in eastern Indonesia, located about 1,000 kilometres east of Java and 2,000 kilometres south of New Guinea. The islands comprise over 700 islands, with a total land area of approximately 245,000 square kilometres. They have a population of around 1 million people, most of whom are Muslim. The largest island group is the Tolo-speaking region, which comprises over 60% of the population.

The Moluccas were first explored by Europeans in 1512. Portuguese explorer João da Nova discovered Ternate and Tidore, while Dutch explorer Jacob Roggeveen discovered Halmahera and Bougainville. The Moluccas were later visited by Spanish explorer Ferdinand Magellan in 1521. British explorer James Cook visited Ternate, Tidore, Halmahera, and Bougainville during his first voyage in 1770–71.

In computer science and mathematics, a full employment theorem is a theorem stating that for any given set of available resources, there exists a unique unemployment equilibrium in which there are no unemployed people.

The full employment theorem is a result of the theory of market equilibrium and was first proposed by Pareto in 1895. The theorem states that if the market has the ability to create full employment, then there will be no unemployment.

There are a few conditions that must be met for the theorem to hold:
1) There must be enough resources available to meet demand.
2) The market must be able to create jobs at the same rate as people enter and leave the workforce.
3) The rate at which jobs are created must be equal to the rate at which people want to work.

Qasr Ibrahim (Ibrahim Palace) is a historical palace in Saint Petersburg, Russia. It is located on the Fontanka River, southeast of the Winter Palace. 

The construction of the palace began in 1754 on the orders of Empress Elizabeth I for her son, Peter III. The palace was built as a residence for the imperial family and remained their primary residence until 1918. From 1918 to 1924 it served as the official residence of the Russian provisional government during the Russian Revolution. 

The palace has been used as a museum since 1924 and is now part of the State Hermitage Museum.

The story is set in the fictional town of Jai Bhim. It follows Bhim (Akshay Kumar), a humble taxi driver who is wrongly accused of a crime he did not commit, and his quest to clear his name and restore justice to his town. 

Development on the film began in early 2019, with Khan directing from a screenplay he wrote himself. Principal photography began in November that year in Mumbai and continued in other parts of Maharashtra until May 2020. The film was shot using anamorphic lenses, to give it a "grittier" look.

The history of Madagascar is distinguished clearly from that of neighbouring islands by its unique blend of traditional and colonial influences. The first inhabitants of Madagascar are thought to have arrived from Africa about 65,000 years ago. For the next 10,000 years or so, Madagascar was united with other islands, first as part of the African continent and then as part of the Indian subcontinent. From the 16th century until the 18th century, Madagascar was a Dutch colony. In 1795 it became a French colony. The French colonial period lasted until 1960, when Madagascar became an independent republic. 

Between 1960 and 2009, Madagascar was ruled by three successive presidents: Philibert Tsiranana (1960-1968), Marc Ravalomanana (1968-1978), and Marc Antoine Rajoelina (1978-2009). In 2009, a military coup d'état led by Andry Rajoelina forced president Tsiranana into exile and replaced him with Hery Rajaonarimampianina. Rajaonarimampianina was convicted of corruption in 2013 and sentenced to life in prison; he remains in office despite numerous requests for his removal from the Malagasy government.

Adaptation is an important process in vision because it enables us to detect objects and scenes that are changing rapidly, such as when we are moving or when something new is happening. Our eyes usually adapt quickly to changes in our environment, but sometimes they can't adapt fast enough or they adapt in the wrong way. This can lead to problems with our vision, like when we can't see in low light or when we get headaches from viewing bright lights.

There are two main types of adaptation: positive and negative. Positive adaptation occurs when the eyes become more sensitive to light, and negative adaptation occurs when the eyes become less sensitive to light.

Transferable development rights (TDR) is a method of transferring development rights in a project from the original developer to another party. The term is most commonly used in the context of real estate development.

The purpose of TDR is to provide a way for the original developer to relinquish control of a project without having to sell the property or give up any ownership rights. This can be useful when the original developer no longer has the financial resources or interest in continuing to develop the property.

Analytical psychology is characterized by its focus on understanding the individual mind and behavior, as opposed to the traditional focus on group behavior and whole person analysis. It has been described as "theoretical psychology with a microscope" because its practitioners are often interested in studying the smallest details of mental processes.

Analytical psychologists often use mathematical modeling and computer simulation to explore how individual thoughts and behaviors can produce outcomes. They are also known for their focus on self-awareness and the ability of the mind to process information.

Ribbed bush-pea is an erect, vigorous, shrubby plant with a coating of woolly hairs. The leaves are alternate and pinnate, the leaflets 10-15 cm long and 4-6 cm broad, the terminal one 4-5 cm long and broad, with a prominent rib on its surface. The flowers are red, with yellow centres, and are produced in clusters at the ends of the branches. The pods are cylindrical, 3-5 cm long and 2-3 cm broad, with a series of prominent ribs. The seed is black and has a rib on its surface.

The crash of Alitalia Flight 618 was a fatal air crash that occurred on 31 October 1978, near Rome, Italy. The aircraft, a McDonnell Douglas DC-9-30 jetliner, was en route from Tel Aviv, Israel to Rome, Italy with 154 passengers and 6 crew members on board. Shortly after takeoff from Rome's Fiumicino Airport, the aircraft crashed into a mountain, killing all onboard.

The cause of the accident is still under investigation, with various theories put forward including a possible high-speed stall or loss of control. The flight data recorder and cockpit voice recorder were not recovered and have not been fully analyzed.

Boris Abbott Jacobsohn (30 July 1918, New York City – 25 December 2006, Woodstock, New York) was an American composer, conductor and pianist.

Jacobsohn was born in New York City, the son of Russian-born immigrant Boris Jacobsohn and his wife, the pianist Annette Jacobsohn. He began studying piano at the age of five with his mother and continued his studies with Felix Weingartner and Alfred Cortot. He also studied conducting with Fritz Reiner and composition with Arnold Schoenberg.

Jacobsohn made his debut as a conductor in 1944 at the age of 22 with the New York Philharmonic. He became music director of the Cincinnati Symphony Orchestra in 1948 and remained in that position until 1964. During his tenure the orchestra won many awards, including seven Grammy Awards. Jacobsohn also served as music director of the Berlin Philharmonic from 1961 to 1964. In 1969 he became the first American to be appointed chief conductor of the Vienna Philharmonic.

Jacobsohn was known for his eclectic style and his recordings of both classical and popular music. He was also a noted teacher, having taught at several universities, including Columbia University, where he founded the school of music. Jacobsohn died in Woodstock, New York, aged 88.

, also known as Attorney General v. Khan, is a United States Supreme Court case in which the Court ruled 5-4 that the federal government cannot compel a person to provide genetic information to a government agency.

The case arises from an appeal by Agha Khan, the son of the spiritual leader of the Ismaili Muslims, against a decision by the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) to require him to provide a genealogical sample to verify his familial relationship to other individuals who applied for federal health benefits. Khan argued that compliance with the request would violate his right to privacy under the Fourth Amendment of the United States Constitution.

The case was heard by the Supreme Court in 2016. On June 23, 2016, the Court ruled in favor of Khan, holding that requiring him to provide a genealogical sample would violate his right to privacy.

High Road is a 2011 American improvised road film written and directed by Will Forte. The film was produced by Forte and Phil Lord, who also co-wrote the film with Forte. The cast includes Forte, Kristen Wiig, Melonie Diaz, Lewis Black, John Slattery, and Jon Hamm.

The film is set on a long stretch of highway in the American Midwest that has been abandoned for years. The only people left are an aging couple (Forte and Wiig) and their young daughter (Diaz). They're trying to make it through the winter while waiting for the road to be fixed so they can go back home. 

The film is shot in continuous long takes, with no cuts except for brief moments when the characters break for food or shelter. Critics praised the film's unconventional style and found it difficult to determine where one scene ended and the next began.

High Road was released in select theaters on April 13, 2011, before being released on DVD and Blu-Ray on May 10, 2011.

Alejandro Celestino Toledo Manrique (; born 28 January 1966) is a Mexican politician affiliated with the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI). He served as the 36th President of Mexico from 2006 to 2012.

Toledo was born in Tijuana, Baja California, the son of Celia de los Ángeles Toledo and Alejandro Manrique. He obtained his secondary education in Tijuana. In 1988 he obtained a degree in economics from the Universidad Autónoma de Baja California. That same year he joined the PRI.

In 1994 he became deputy of Tijuana. In 2000 he was elected Governor of Baja California, a position he held until 2004. In 2006 he was elected President of Mexico, beating his PRI opponent Felipe Calderón by a wide margin. His term ended in 2012, after which he was succeeded by Enrique Peña Nieto of the PRI.

Toledo is married to Leonor Rivera with three children: Alejandro, Andrea and Valentina.

The Drummond family remained in ownership of Fetteresso Castle until 1782, when it was sold to Colonel George Maxwell. Figure-ground contrast, in the context of mapmaking, is the difference between the shapes and sizes of the features depicted on a map and the spaces around them. The term generally applies to maps of real or imaginary landscapes, but can also be used for maps of abstract concepts.

Figure-ground contrast is an important consideration in mapmaking because it affects how viewers interact with a map. For instance, if most of the features on a map are large and well-defined, viewers may feel overwhelmed and lose their sense of orientation. If, on the other hand, most features are small and subtle, viewers may be more likely to notice and appreciate them.

In cartography, figure-ground contrast is often achieved through the use of scale. Large features are typically drawn at a larger scale than smaller features, in order to make them more noticeable. Conversely, smaller features are typically drawn at a smaller scale than larger features, in order to preserve their visibility.

Figure-ground contrast is also important for portraying information on a map. For instance, if a map contains a lot of information about one specific area, it may be difficult to see if that information is balanced among the various features on the map. By contrasting large areas with small areas, cartographers can help to improve legibility.

There are about 165 genera and 2,000 species of capers, distributed worldwide in temperate and tropical climates.

The capers are a terrestrial or semiterrestrial family of flowering plants. They are herbs or small shrubs, with fleshy leaves that are either alternate or opposite and entire or toothed. The flowers are arranged in spikelike inflorescences, each with a few small sepals and petals. The fruit is a tiny Capsicum, typically a pepper but sometimes a fruit that resembles a tomato. The genus Capparis contains the typical capers (Capparis spinosa) and the related genus Ceratonia contains the false capers (Ceratonia siliqua), which have edible fruits resembling those of the true capers.

The capers are native to Europe, North Africa, the Middle East, Asia Minor, and North America. They have been naturalized in many other parts of the world. They grow best in slightly alkaline soil with good drainage and moderate fertility.

Tolerable daily intake (TDI) refers to the maximum safe amount of a particular nutrient or food that can be consumed daily without causing any adverse health consequences.

The tolerable daily intake is the maximum safe amount of a nutrient or food that can be consumed daily without causing any adverse health consequences. The tolerable daily intake is determined by the Food and Nutrition Board of the National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine.

The tolerable daily intake does not reflect the recommended dietary allowance (RDA), which is the amount of a nutrient that is thought to provide optimum health for most people. Currency war, also known as competitive devaluations, is a situation in which two or more countries attempt to lower the value of their currencies to gain an advantage in exports over their rivals.

Currency wars have been observed throughout history, and are often the result of bilateral trade deficits. One country may attempt to reduce the value of its currency in order to make its exports more competitive, while the opposing country may respond by doing the same. This process can lead to a sustained decrease in the value of currencies, which can have negative consequences for both economies.

It is a philosophical and methodological approach that began to develop in the 1940s and 1950s and has been influential in sociology, anthropology, and psychology. Interactionism has a number of important implications for sociology. Finally, it stresses the importance of social interaction as a means of learning and understanding behaviour.

The album reached number 6 on the UK Albums Chart and number 4 on the US Billboard 200. It has been certified triple platinum by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA).

Hedjkheperre Setepenre Shoshenq IV was an ancient Egyptian pharaoh of the Twenty-second Dynasty. He ruled from 945 BC to 925 BC.

Shoshenq IV was the son of Hedjkheperre Setepenre and his wife Tiy-Merenese. He was the successor of his father, who probably died during the battle against the Libyans in 945 BC. According to a stela from Abydos, Shoshenq IV was buried in a tomb near the pyramid of Menkaure, and he was succeeded by his son, Takelot I.

Shoshenq IV is most noted for his Great Inscription, which records the Donation of the Index of Thoth and other monuments from Karnak. The inscription reads:

"Year 5, 3rd month of Shoshenq III, day 22,
"The great king, Shoshenq III, beloved of Ra, given life, triumphant in battle - he establishes for all time a monument to himself in the sacred temple of Amun at Karnak."

Also notable is his papyri collection, now in the British Museum.

He fought in the Waikato campaign of 1863 and later served in campaigns against the Māori. In 1868 he left New Zealand for Victoria, Australia, where he engaged in sheep farming. 

In 1876 O'Hea travelled to North Queensland where he became involved in cattle grazing and mining ventures. He was elected to the Queensland Legislative Assembly as a Nationalist member for Rockhampton East in 1884, serving until his defeat in 1888. From 1886 to 1889 he was Minister for Mines and Public Works. O'Hea also served as a lieutenant colonel in the Queensland Volunteers during part of the Second Boer War. He died at Rockhampton in 1902 aged 67.

They also appear to have been involved in agriculture, herding camel herds, and mining. The Quda'a were also known for their piety and their adherence to a number of religious beliefs, including Islam.

The Quda'a were eventually destroyed by the Christian Byzantine Empire in the 5th century AD.

The rise of punk rock in the late 1970s created a demand for new and used LPs, which were less available on CD at that time. The second vinyl revival began in the early 2000s and has been most notable in Europe and Japan. This revival was spurred by technological advances that made it possible to play vinyl records on turntables that were not usually used for music playback. Political jurisprudence is a legal theory that deals with the interpretation and application of the law in relation to politics.

Political jurisprudence is a legal theory that deals with the interpretation and application of the law in relation to politics. It is concerned with understanding how, when, and why the law has been used to regulate political activity, and how it has been applied in specific cases. Political jurisprudence also considers how the law should be changed or adapted to meet the changing needs of political society.

One of the most important goals of political jurisprudence is to ensure that the law is applied equitably and fairly. This means that judges must take into account all relevant factors when ruling on cases, including the political context in which they arose, the interests of the parties involved, and the larger implications of the decision.

Political jurisprudence has played an important role in shaping the development of modern democracy. It has helped to ensure that all citizens have a fair chance to participate in political life, and that government actions are based on sound legal principles.

Late Greek means writings in the Greek language produced after the end of the Byzantine Empire in 1453. It is considered to be a continuation of Byzantine Greek.

The Byzantine Empire, which was founded in 330 AD, was one of the most influential political and cultural forces in the Mediterranean for more than 800 years. Its decline began in the 11th century and by the end of the 13th century, it had lost all its territory in Anatolia to the Turkish Ottoman Empire. The Empire continued to exist as an autonomous Orthodox Christian polity under the rule of the Ottoman Sultan until its dissolution in 1917.

The Late Greek period is generally considered to comprise writings produced in Greek between c. 1453 and 1537, although some authors from earlier periods are also included. This period is marked by a renewed interest in classical antiquity, as well as a flowering of literature and art. Significant writers from this period include Manuel Chrysoloras, George Gemistos Plethon, and Constantine Laskaris.

The concept of business process orientation (BPO) emerged in the early 1990s as a response to the challenge of managing business processes in an increasingly complex and globalized world. BPO is a way of organizing the work that companies do to deliver their products or services. 

BPO is based on the idea that businesses should break down their processes into smaller, more manageable tasks, and then assign specific individuals or teams to complete those tasks. This approach helps companies to improve their efficiency and effectiveness by ensuring that the tasks that need to be completed are done in a coordinated manner. 

In addition, BPO helps companies to understand their customers better by understanding the steps that they take to purchase products or services. By understanding these steps, companies can make more informed decisions about their products or services.

The Freedman's Saving and Trust Company, known as Freedman's Bank, was a historic African-American financial institution in the United States.

Freedman's Bank was founded in 1852 by a group of freed slaves and their white allies. Initially, the bank offered small loans and savings accounts to its customers. In 1865, Freedman's Bank became the first African American bank to open in the city of Chicago. Over the course of its history, Freedman's Bank played an important role in the development of African-American business and financial institutions.

In 1907, with the help of noted African American banker E. Franklin Frazier, Freedman's Bank became one of the first black-owned banks to be publicly traded on the New York Stock Exchange. In 1986, Freedman's Bank merged with the Chicago-based People's Savings and Loan Company to form what is now known as TCF Bank.

In macroeconomics, the classical dichotomy is the distinction between market and planned economies. It is based on the differing assumptions made about the behavior of economic agents under market and planning conditions.

In a market economy, agents are assumed to be rational and self-interested. They will seek to maximize their profits, and will act in their own best interests. The allocation of resources will be determined by the interactions between these agents.

In a planned economy, agents are assumed to be committed to the common good. They will aim to fulfill the needs of the population as a whole, rather than focusing on individual profit. Planning decisions are based on a understanding of the future needs of society, rather than on current economic conditions.

The classical dichotomy has been challenged by recent research which suggests that there is little difference between market and planned economies in terms of their impact on social welfare.

Public safety diving can be performed in any body of water, including oceans, lakes, rivers, and reservoirs. It can be used to perform tasks such as Search and Rescue (SAR), water rescue, firefighting, and environmental assessment.

Public safety diving is a highly specialized field that requires extensive training and experience. In order to become a certified public safety diver, one must complete an accredited training program that includes both theoretical and practical learning experiences.

Recurrent brief depression (RBD) defines a mental disorder characterized by episodes of major depression, which usually last for no more than two weeks, but may persist for months or even years. RBD is a relatively new diagnosis that was first recognized in the early 1990s. It is estimated that 1-2% of adults experience RBD at some point in their lives.

The precise cause of RBD is unknown, but it appears to be caused by a combination of genetic and environmental factors. Some people with RBD are also at increased risk for developing recurrent major depression.

RBD can be very difficult to treat, and patients typically require ongoing treatment to maintain remission. Treatment options include medication, psychotherapy, and electroconvulsive therapy (ECT).

There is currently no cure for RBD, but treatments can help improve symptoms and lead to improved quality of life.

The Atlantic semi-deciduous forests, also known as the Atlantic hardwood and pine-oak forests, are a temperate broadleaf and mixed forest ecoregion of the North American Cordillera, stretching from southeastern Quebec and eastern New Brunswick in Canada south to the northernmost tip of Florida in the United States.

The Atlantic semi-deciduous forests are one of the most diverse ecoregions in North America. They are home to a wide variety of plants and animals, including more than 350 plant species, 75 mammal species, 20 bird species, and 10 amphibian species. The forests are rich in natural resources, including timber, minerals, and wildlife.

The Atlantic semi-deciduous forests are threatened by a number of factors. Habitat destruction and degradation due to logging, development, and wildfires is the main cause of concern. Climate change is also a threat, as warmer temperatures increase the prevalence of pests and diseases, which can damage trees and disrupt the distribution of forest insects.

Stevens was born in Kensington, London, the son of Sir Sydney Stevens, 1st Baronet and his wife, the former Florence Barnsdale. He was educated at Eton and Trinity College, Cambridge.

At the 1918 general election, Stevens was elected as Member of Parliament (MP) for Tamworth in Staffordshire. He held the seat until it was abolished in 1950. Between 1924 and 1929 he served as Parliamentary Private Secretary to Sir Austen Chamberlain, the Conservative Prime Minister.

In 1940, Stevens became Secretary of State for War in Winston Churchill's wartime coalition government. In this role, he played a central role in the British response to Operation Barbarossa, the Nazi invasion of the Soviet Union. 

In July 1945, Stevens resigned from the government over disagreements about the future of British colonialism. He did not contest the 1945 general election and retired from politics. 

Stevens served as Chairman of Imperial Airways from 1946 to 1949 and as President of the Royal Academy of Engineering from 1951 to 1952. In 1959, he was made a Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath (KCB). 

Stevens died at his home in London aged 78. He was succeeded in his baronetcy by his son, Sydney Barnsdale Stevens.

Liberal-Progressives believed that liberalism could be adapted to new social, economic, and technological realities, and that progressives could play an important role in liberal politics. They advocated for a range of progressive reforms, including civil rights, women's rights, environmentalism, and gay rights.

The label has been used sparsely since the late 1970s, but it has been revived in recent years to describe a contemporary strain of liberalism that is more open to progressive ideals than traditional liberalism.

In basketball, a technical foul (colloquially known as a "tech") is a penalty assessed to a player by the referee for unsportsmanlike conduct. A technical foul is one of several penalties available to the referee, which can be called for various reasons, such as ball-stopping, arguing with the referee, or physical contact with an opponent. In some cases, when a technical foul is called against a player who is already in violation of the rules, that player will be assessed another technical foul.

A technical foul results in a player being ejected from the game and may also lead to a suspension from future games. A second technical foul results in an automatic ejection; any subsequent technical fouls will result in additional ejections. If a player accumulates three technical fouls in a game, they are automatically ejected from the game and must be replaced by a substitute.

Length of pull is important for two reasons. The first reason is that it affects the balance of a firearm. A firearm with a shorter LOP will be more stable in the hand, while a firearm with a longer LOP will be less stable. The second reason is that it affects how easily the firearm can be pulled back. Rodney Stuart Young (born August 1, 1907, died January 21, 1988) was an American archaeologist who specialized in the study of the Pre-Columbian cultures of the Americas.

Born in Missoula, Montana, Young received his B.A. from the University of Utah in 1931 and his M.A. from Harvard University in 1933. He then served as an instructor at the University of Utah from 1933 to 1935, before receiving a fellowship to study at the University of Berlin. He returned to America in 1937 and became an instructor at Cornell University. In 1942 he was appointed associate professor at the University of California, Berkeley, where he remained until his retirement in 1978.

During his forty-year career, Young directed or participated in excavations at more than thirty archaeological sites in Mexico, Central America, and South America. His major publications include The Pre-Columbian Cultures of Mesoamerica (1953), The Maya Sculpture Style (1957), and The Art of Ancient Mesoamerica (1978). He also wrote numerous articles and book chapters on Pre-Columbian art and archaeology.

Ra's al-'Ayn camps (also Ras ul-Ain camps) were a series of detention and concentration camps operated by the Syrian Government during the Syrian Civil War. The camps were located in Ras al-'Ayn, Idlib Governorate.

The camps were initially established in May 2013 to house detainees who had been captured by the Syrian Army during the Battle of Ras al-Ayn. As the war continued, more and more people were detained in the camps, including civilians and rebel fighters. Conditions in the camps were harsh, with little food or water available. In October 2016, an Amnesty International report found that detainees in Ras al-Ayn had been subjected to torture and other ill-treatment.

The Cuillin ( or ) is a mountain range in the Highlands of Scotland. The range extends for about 32 miles (51 km) from the north-west coast of Skye to the north-east coast of Lochaber. The highest peak, Cuillin Munro, is about 4,309 feet (1,321 m) high.

The Cuillin is a popular tourist destination for walkers, climbers and mountain bikers. The range provides a wide range of habitats including moorland, heathland and montane forest. There are over sixty named peaks in the range and many other summits with rough and unclimbed terrain making them ideal for exploring on foot or by bike.

There are several reasons for conducting monitor proofing. One reason is to make sure that all the content in a document is accurate. Another reason is to make sure that all of the formatting is correct. Finally, monitor proofing can be used to check for typos and other errors.

-Check each sentence for correctness
-Check for spelling and grammar mistakes
-Check for formatting issues
-Check for consistency throughout the document

Bloody Creek crater, which is also known as the Bloody Creek caldera, is a large and symmetrical volcanic crater located in the Southern Alps of New Zealand. The crater is about 150 metres in diameter and up to 50 metres deep.

The crater was formed about 1.5 million years ago by an eruption of the Mount Arthur Volcanic Group. The eruption produced a large volume of ash, which was carried by the wind to the North-West and deposited over a wide area including Bloody Creek. This ash layer has preserved many features of the pre-existing landscape including moraines, lakes, and valleys.

Today, Bloody Creek is a popular tourist destination due to its beauty and historical significance. The crater is home to a number of rare plants and animals, including the endemic southern beech tree.

Black July (;  Kalu Juliya) was a month-long period of civil unrest in Sri Lanka in 1983. The events leading to the unrest are still disputed.

On 7 July 1983, the military government of Sri Lanka announced a series of free and fair elections for the month of November. However, the military government also introduced a new security law, the Defense and Security Act, which was seen by many as an attempt to curtail political opposition. This led to protests and large demonstrations throughout the country.

On 18 July 1983, a group of soldiers marched on the Presidential Palace in Colombo, demanding that President J. R. Jayawardene step down. After negotiations failed, the soldiers stormed the palace and took President Jayawardene hostage. The next day, 19 July, the military responded with a violent crackdown on civilian protesters. This is now known as Black July. Over the course of the next several days, over 300 people were killed and thousands were injured. The military government eventually lost control of the country and was replaced by a democratic government in 1986.

Grant worked as a journalist before becoming a full-time suffragette in 1913. She was arrested for protesting against the male-only franchise in 1918, and served three months in Holloway Prison. Grant became a prominent figure in the women's suffrage movement, and was a member of the executive committee of the Women's Social and Political Union (WSPU) from 1922 to 1938. She also served as president of the British Federation of Women's Institutes from 1930 to 1949.

Grant wrote two books about her life as a suffragette: The Road to Votes for Women (1929) and Footsteps Along the Way (1951). She also published articles about women's rights in magazines such as The Observer and The Times. Grant served as a BBC broadcaster from 1945 to 1958, and she was awarded an MBE in 1951. She died in 1983.

The 1910 Cuba hurricane, popularly known as the Great Hurricane of 1910, was the most intense and destructive hurricane in the history of Cuba. Formed on October 25 near the Lesser Antilles, the hurricane rapidly strengthened as it moved towards the Caribbean Sea. On October 29, the hurricane made landfall near Yara, Cuba as a Category 4 storm with winds estimated at 185 mph (300 km/h). The cyclone rapidly weakened as it moved over land, and dissipated on November 5 near Key West. The hurricane killed at least 1,500 people in Cuba, injured thousands more, and caused $120 million (1910 USD) in damage.

Royal Air Force Annan or more simply RAF Annan is a Royal Air Force station located north east of the town of Annan, in the Scottish Borders region of Scotland. The station has three operational squadrons; No. 9 Squadron, No. 16 Squadron and No. 43 Squadron RAF, as well as two training squadrons; No. 12 (Training) Squadron and No. 181 (Reserve) Squadron RAF. The base also houses No. 664 Squadron AAC which provides helicopter support to the operational squadrons and the wider military community.

The station was opened on 1 April 1918 as an RAF Advanced Landing Ground during World War I, becoming a Royal Air Force Station on 1 April 1937. During World War II the airfield was used by the United States Army Air Forces Eighth Air Force as part of the British Eighth Air Force strategic bombing campaign against Nazi Germany, with heavy bombardment from the air in support of Operation Overlord, the Allied invasion of Normandy in June 1944. The airfield was liberated by British and Canadian ground forces on 29 July 1944 and became home to Nos. 9, 16 and 43 Squadrons RAF which had flown in from England to help fight the war in Europe. Annan remained a fighter station until 1964 when it became a training establishment for helicopter pilots and support staff with No. 12 (Training) Squadron RAF being formed here in 1967. Everybody, Sing! is a Philippine musical game show produced by GMA Network. The show is hosted by Piolo Pascual and Kathryn Bernardo and airs every Sunday at 7:00pm (PST).

The show pits a team of celebrities against each other in various singing challenges. The first team to finish their challenge is the winner. As of April 2017, the show has aired for 159 episodes.

The show was created by GMA Network head Vhong Navarro who initially wanted to create a family-friendly singing competition show similar to American Idol but with a Filipino twist. Navarro initially approached ABS-CBN Corporation about producing the show but they declined, so GMA Network decided to produce it themselves.

The original cast of the show consisted of Piolo Pascual, Bea Alonzo, Diether Ocampo, Janine Gutierrez, and John Lloyd Cruz. However, after Cruz's departure from the show due to personal reasons, Lloyd reprised his role as host for the remaining episodes.

Janet Schulman (16 September 1933 – 11 October 2016) was an American author and screenwriter. She was the first woman to win the prestigious Edgar Award, given by the Mystery Writers of America for best novel.

Born in Brooklyn, New York, Schulman studied at Barnard College and received her MA from Columbia University. She worked as a librarian before turning to writing full-time. Her debut novel, A Friend of the Family, was published in 1971 and won the Edgar Award. Two more novels followed, both of which were also Edgar nominees: The Good Sister (1973) and What Alice Forgot (1975).

In 1978 Schulman wrote her screenplay for the film version of What Alice Forgot, which starred Kathleen Turner and James Spader. The film was well-received by critics and earned Schulman a nomination for an Academy Award for Best Screenplay. She continued to write screenplays throughout the 1970s and 1980s, including for such films as Death on the Nile (1978), The Spy Who Loved Me (1981), and Three Days of the Condor (1975).

Schulman retired from writing in the 1990s but continued to publish novels sporadically until her death in 2016 at the age of 88.
